<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-perfect-squares" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Perfect Squares</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.3 Quadratic Expressions and Equations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Derive the quadratic identities from the concept of area
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand what perfect square trinomials are and recognize the two perfect square identities: <m>(a+b)^2</m> and <m>(a-b)^2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Expand perfect squares and factor perfect square trinomials using the identities.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Use perfect square identities to simplify expressions and solve problems more efficiently.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/quadratic-expressions-and-equations/perfect-squares.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/quadratic-expressions-and-equations/step-by-step-guide_perfect-squares.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To explore perfect square identities, expanding perfect squares, and recognizing and factoring perfect square trinomials.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    Groups define and discuss: perfect square identities, expanding perfect squares, recognizing perfect square trinomials, and factoring them.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Copy and Observe:</alert>
                    <ol marker="(i)">
                        <li><m>(a+b)^2 = a^2 + 2ab + b^2</m></li>
                        <li><m>(a-b)^2 = a^2 - 2ab + b^2</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Key Observation:</alert> The middle term is TWICE the product of the two terms.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Discussion questions about how recognizing perfect square trinomials makes factoring easier, and real-world applications of perfect square identities.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    The teacher asks probing questions such as: <q>Can you verify by expanding?</q>, <q>What do you notice about the middle term?</q>, and <q>How can you tell if a trinomial is a perfect square?</q>. The teacher uses learner discoveries to bridge to formal instruction on perfect square identities.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>
    <activity xml:id="activity_perfect_squares_geometric_explore">
        <!-- <title>Exploring the Area of a Square with Side Length <m>(a+b)</m></title> -->

        <p>
            Study the diagram below carefully. Use what you know about area to investigate what is happening.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig_perfect_square_expansion">
            <caption>Geometric Decomposition of <m>(a+b)^2</m></caption>
            <image xml:id="img_perfect_square_expansion" width="60%">
                <shortdescription>A square with side length (a+b) divided into four colored regions representing a^2, 2ab, and b^2</shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
                    \pgfmathsetmacro{\a}{2.4}
                    \pgfmathsetmacro{\b}{1.6}
                    \pgfmathsetmacro{\aplusb}{\a+\b}
                    \pgfmathsetmacro{\amid}{\a/2}
                    \pgfmathsetmacro{\bmid}{\b/2}
                    \pgfmathsetmacro{\halfab}{\aplusb/2}

                    % Fill regions
                    \fill[blue!25] (0,\b) rectangle (\a,\aplusb);
                    \fill[green!25] (0,0) rectangle (\a,\b);
                    \fill[green!25] (\a,\b) rectangle (\aplusb,\aplusb);
                    \fill[red!25] (\a,0) rectangle (\aplusb,\b);

                    % Draw borders
                    \draw[thick] (0,0) rectangle (\aplusb,\aplusb);
                    \draw[dashed,gray!40] (\a,0) -- (\a,\aplusb);
                    \draw[dashed,gray!40] (0,\b) -- (\aplusb,\b);

                    % Dimension lines and labels - Bottom
                    \draw[|-|] (-0.35,-0.25) -- (-0.35+\a,-0.25);
                    \node[anchor=north,inner sep=2pt] at (-0.35+\amid,-0.35) {\(\mathbf{a}\)};

                    \draw[|-|] (-0.35+\a,-0.25) -- (-0.35+\aplusb,-0.25);
                    \node[anchor=north,inner sep=2pt] at (-0.35+\a+\bmid,-0.35) {\(\mathbf{b}\)};

                    % Dimension lines - Left
                    \draw[|-|] (-0.5,0) -- (-0.5,\b);
                    \node[anchor=east,inner sep=2pt] at (-0.62,\bmid) {\(\mathbf{b}\)};

                    \draw[|-|] (-0.5,\b) -- (-0.5,\aplusb);
                    \node[anchor=east,inner sep=2pt] at (-0.62,\b+\amid) {\(\mathbf{a}\)};

                    % Total dimensions
                    \draw[|-|] (\aplusb+0.25,0) -- (\aplusb+0.25,\aplusb);
                    \node[anchor=west,inner sep=2pt] at (\aplusb+0.4,\halfab) {\(\mathbf{a+b}\)};

                    \draw[|-|] (0,\aplusb+0.3) -- (\aplusb,\aplusb+0.3);
                    \node[anchor=south,inner sep=2pt] at (\halfab,\aplusb+0.4) {\(\mathbf{a+b}\)};

                    % Region labels
                    %\node[font=\Large\bfseries,blue!60] at (\amid,\b+\amid) {\(a^2\)};
                    \node[font=\Large\bfseries,green!60] at (\amid,\bmid) {\(ab\)};
                    %\node[font=\Large\bfseries,green!60] at (\a+\bmid,\b+\amid) {\(ab\)};
                    %\node[font=\Large\bfseries,red!60] at (\a+\bmid,\bmid) {\(b^2\)};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <p>
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Find the areas of the smaller regions
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="(a)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Identify the side lengths of each colored region; the blue square, the two green rectangles, and the red square.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Add all these smaller areas together.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Write your total area as a simplified algebraic expression.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                         Find the area of the large square
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="(a)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    What is the total length of one side of the large outer square?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Using the formula for the area of a square, calculate the area of the whole square directly.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Express your answer in algebraic form.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Compare your results
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="(a)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Compare the total area you found by adding the smaller parts with the area you found using the side length of the large square.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Are the two expressions the same?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    What conclusion can you make about <m>(a+b)^2</m>?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        How does breaking a square into smaller regions help explain why <m>(a+b)^2</m> expands the way it does? 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        What does each smaller region represent in the expansion?
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formally define perfect square trinomials and present the two perfect square identities.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Key Concepts</title>
                <p>
                    <alert>Definition of Perfect Square:</alert> A perfect square trinomial is a trinomial that results from squaring a binomial.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Two Perfect Square Identities:</alert>
                </p>
                <table>
                    <tabular halign="center">
                        <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                            <cell>Identity</cell>
                            <cell>Expansion</cell>
                            <cell>Factored Form</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row bottom="minor">
                            <cell>Identity 1 (<m>+</m>)</cell>
                            <cell><m>a^2 + 2ab + b^2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(a+b)^2</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Identity 2 (<m>-</m>)</cell>
                            <cell><m>a^2 - 2ab + b^2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(a-b)^2</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
                <p>
                    <alert>When to use each:</alert> Use Identity 1 when the middle term is positive; use Identity 2 when the middle term is negative.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>How to recognize a perfect square trinomial:</alert> The first term is a perfect square, the last term is a perfect square, and the middle term equals <m>2 \times \sqrt{\text{first}} \times \sqrt{\text{last}}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Misconception Alert:</alert> <q>Not every trinomial is a perfect square! Check that the middle term is EXACTLY twice the product of the square roots of the first and last terms.</q>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>
    <!-- <insight>
        <p>
            An <alert>integer</alert> that can be written as the product of two equal integers is called a <em><term>perfect square</term></em>. For example, <m>16</m> is a perfect square because it can be expressed as <m>4 \times 4</m>, and <m>25</m> is a perfect square because it can be expressed as <m>5 \times 5.</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>A perfect square identity</alert> represents the square of a binomial<fn>A binomial is a type of algebraic expression (polynomial) that consists of exactly two terms connected by a plus (<m>+</m>) or minus (<m>-</m>) sign.</fn>, resulting in a quadratic expression. These identities are essential tools in algebra for expanding expressions and factoring quadratic equations.
        </p>
        <p>
            The two primary perfect square identities are:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>(a+b)^2 = a^2 + 2ab + b^2</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m> (a - b)^2 = a^2 - 2ab +b^2  </m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </insight> -->
    <insight>
        <p>
            An <alert>integer</alert> that can be written as the product of two equal integers is called a 
            <term>perfect square</term>. 
            For example, <m>16</m> is a perfect square because 
            <m>16 = 4 \times 4</m>, and <m>25</m> is a perfect square because <m>25 = 5 \times 5</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            In algebra, a <alert>perfect square identity</alert> describes what happens when a 
            <term>binomial</term><fn>A binomial is an algebraic expression made up of exactly two terms joined by a plus (<m>+</m>) or minus (<m>-</m>) sign.</fn> 
            is multiplied by itself. The result is a quadratic expression.
        </p>
        <p>
            The two main perfect square identities are:
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <m>(a+b)^2 = a^2 + 2ab + b^2</m>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <m>(a-b)^2 = a^2 - 2ab + b^2</m>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            These identities are important because they help us expand expressions 
            and recognize special patterns when factoring quadratic expressions.
        </p>
    </insight>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Expand and simplify: <m>(x + 5)^2</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Use the perfect square identity 
                <m>(a+b)^2 = a^2 + 2ab + b^2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Here, <m>a = x</m> and <m>b = 5</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                (x+5)^2 = x^2 + 2(x)(5) + 5^2 
                = x^2 + 10x + 25.
                </m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Expand and simplify: <m>(2y - 3)^2</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Use the perfect square identity 
                <m>(a-b)^2 = a^2 - 2ab + b^2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Here, <m>a = 2y</m> and <m>b = 3</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                (2y - 3)^2 = (2y)^2 - 2(2y)(3) + 3^2 
                = 4y^2 - 12y + 9.
                </m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Show that <m>9x^2 + 24x + 16</m> is a perfect square and express it in factorized form.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Compare the expression with the identity 
                <m>(a+b)^2 = a^2 + 2ab + b^2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                9x^2 = (3x)^2, \quad 16 = 4^2, 
                \quad \text{and} \quad 2(3x)(4) = 24x.
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore,
                <m>
                9x^2 + 24x + 16 = (3x + 4)^2.
                </m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Consolidation</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To practice expanding and factoring perfect square trinomials using the identities.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Worked Example</title>
                <p>
                    <alert>Factor <m>x^2 + 6x + 9</m>:</alert>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Step 1:</alert> <m>x^2</m> is a perfect square (<m>\sqrt{x^2} = x</m>), <m>9</m> is a perfect square (<m>\sqrt{9} = 3</m>), and <m>6x = 2 \times x \times 3 = 2ab</m> ✓.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Step 2:</alert> <m>a = x</m>, <m>b = 3</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Step 3:</alert> <m>x^2 + 6x + 9 = (x+3)^2</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>More Practice</title>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li><m>x^2 - 10x + 25 = (x-5)^2</m> (negative middle term).</li>
                        <li>Expand <m>(2x+5)^2 = 4x^2 + 20x + 25</m>.</li>
                        <li><m>4y^2 + 12y + 9</m>: <m>a = 2y</m>, <m>b = 3</m>, <m>12y = 2(2y)(3)</m> ✓ <m>\rightarrow (2y+3)^2</m>.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    The teacher emphasizes the three-step check: (1) Is the first term a perfect square? (2) Is the last term a perfect square? (3) Does the middle term equal twice the product of the square roots?
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>
    <exercises xml:id="exercises-perfect-squares-identity">
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Expand and simplify the following expressions:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li><m>(x + 7)^2</m></li>
                        <li><m>(3a - 2)^2</m></li>
                        <li><m>(2m + 5n)^2</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li><m>x^2 + 14x + 49</m></li>
                        <li><m>9a^2 - 12a + 4</m></li>
                        <li><m>4m^2 + 20mn + 25n^2</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Show that <m>x^2 - 10x + 25</m> is a perfect square and write it in factorized form.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>
                    x^2 - 10x + 25 = (x - 5)^2
                    </m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Factorize: <m>16y^2 + 40y + 25</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>
                    16y^2 + 40y + 25 = (4y + 5)^2
                    </m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Determine whether <m>4x^2 + 12x + 7</m> is a perfect square. Give a reason for your answer.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    It is not a perfect square because 
                    <m>4x^2 = (2x)^2</m> and 
                    <m>7</m> is not a perfect square, 
                    and the middle term <m>12x</m> does not match 
                    <m>2(2x)(\sqrt{7})</m>. 
                    Therefore, it cannot be written in the form <m>(a+b)^2</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

    </exercises>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment / Exit Ticket</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Questions</title>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Factor:
                                <ol marker="(a)">
                                    <li><m>x^2 + 8x + 16</m></li>
                                    <li><m>x^2 - 14x + 49</m></li>
                                    <li><m>9a^2 + 6a + 1</m></li>
                                </ol>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Expand:
                                <ol marker="(a)">
                                    <li><m>(x+4)^2</m></li>
                                    <li><m>(3y-2)^2</m></li>
                                </ol>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Is <m>x^2 + 5x + 6</m> a perfect square trinomial? If yes, factor it.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                A square tile has sides of length <m>(x+2)</m> cm. Write the area in expanded form.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Complete: <m>x^2 + 10x + \underline{\hspace{1cm}} = (x + \underline{\hspace{1cm}})^2</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Answer Key</title>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <ol marker="(a)">
                                    <li><m>(x+4)^2</m></li>
                                    <li><m>(x-7)^2</m></li>
                                    <li><m>(3a+1)^2</m></li>
                                </ol>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <ol marker="(a)">
                                    <li><m>x^2 + 8x + 16</m></li>
                                    <li><m>9y^2 - 12y + 4</m></li>
                                </ol>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                NOT a perfect square <mdash/> the middle term should be approximately <m>4.9x</m>, not <m>5x</m>. It factors as <m>(x+2)(x+3)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>x^2 + 4x + 4</m> cm<m>^2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>25</m>, <m>(x+5)^2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation and Extension</title>
        <table>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <col width="20%"/>
                <col width="55%"/>
                <col width="25%"/>
                <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                    <cell>Learner Level</cell>
                    <cell>Strategies / Activities</cell>
                    <cell>Resources</cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Provide identity reference cards. Use color coding to distinguish <m>a^2</m>, <m>2ab</m>, and <m>b^2</m>. Start with numerical examples (e.g., <m>4 + 4 + 1 = 9 = 3^2</m>). Pair with a peer for guided support.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>The core lesson activities as described above.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert></line>
                        <line>1. Factor <m>x^4 + 4x^2 + 4</m>.</line>
                        <line>2. If <m>(x+k)^2 = x^2 + 12x + c</m>, find <m>k</m> and <m>c</m>.</line>
                        <line>3. Complete the square: <m>x^2 + 6x + 5 = 0</m>.</line>
                        <line>4. Prove <m>(a+b+c)^2 = a^2 + b^2 + c^2 + 2ab + 2bc + 2ac</m>.</line>
                        <line></line>
                        <line><alert>Solutions:</alert></line>
                        <line>1. <m>x^4 + 4x^2 + 4 = (x^2)^2 + 2(x^2)(2) + 2^2 = (x^2+2)^2</m>.</line>
                        <line>2. <m>2k = 12 \rightarrow k = 6</m>, <m>c = k^2 = 36</m>.</line>
                        <line>3. <m>x^2 + 6x + 5 = 0 \rightarrow x^2 + 6x + 9 = 4 \rightarrow (x+3)^2 = 4 \rightarrow x + 3 = \pm 2 \rightarrow x = -1</m> or <m>x = -5</m>.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>
